## Control page break
For longer documents, i.e. templates with more content than will fit on one print page, the necessary page breaks are automatically inserted in the output document. No page breaks are displayed in the editor, since the number of pages in the output document depends on various factors such as the space required by the dynamic content and the output format - It is not fixed until the document gets rendered.

If required, the page break can be controlled: On the one hand you can prevent the separation of elements by a page break by holding elements together. On the other hand you can force a page break at a certain position. The necessary attributes for both can be found under `Style &amp; Properties &gt; Advanced &gt; Keeps and Breaks`.

To keep elements together on the same page use the keep-with… or keep-together… attribute.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Keep together means: if the elements cannot fit on one page, they are placed together on the next page.

For example, if a block should always be on the same page as the block above it, set the keep-with-previous.within-page attribute to "always".

If all text elements within a block should always stay together, set the keep-together.within- page attribute for the block to "always".

To force a page break, set the attribute break-after for the last element of the page to "page". This will cause a page break after this element.

> Note

*This attribute is only available for block-level elements.*

*![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)*

## Page settings, layout
The page settings are combined in a so-called Page Master. By default, there is only one Page Master named "A4". This is sufficient as long as the same settings should apply to all pages of the output document.

To change the page margins and other page settings, use the "Layout" button in the toolbar to switch to the page master view, then click on "A4" (or the respective Page Master name - see below) and then apply the desired changes on the right.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

> Note

*The name "A4" can be changed, but this can lead to errors - see *[Page Master Name](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-business-designer-user-guide-page-break-page-settings-page-master#notes-on-page-master-names-and-selection). The page format is determined under *Format*. For different formats, you can enter the

dimensions under *Height *and *Width*. To change from portrait to landscape, use the ![](data:image/png;base64,) - icon to switch the height and width dimensions.

**Page regions and Precedence**: The region names of the page regions can be seen here - see also chapter [Static Content](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-business-designer-user-guide-static-page-contents-headers-footers-page-numbers). Since there are four "static page regions" (top, bottom, left, right), they might overlap at the corners. The *Precedence *determines whether the corners are occupied by the header/footer or the left/right region.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Precedence top and bottom

![](data:image/png;base64,)

**No precedence **top and bottom

Changing region names is only relevant in context with complex page masters - see [Complex Page Master](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-business-designer-user-guide-page-break-page-settings-page-master#different-page-layouts-in-one-document-complex-page-masters).

> Note

*Never change the region names unless you are using a complex page master! Otherwise the document cannot be rendered anymore, even if you change the range names back to the original value.*

The position of the template content is defined in XSL-FO by **three **types of boundaries: **page margins, body margins** and **extents**.

Note that you can only see (and change) the body margins when you mouse over the layout view - another set of values will appear within the page margin values, these are the body margins.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

You can drag the blue markers if you want to change the page margins or body margins. Or you can use the ![](data:image/png;base64,) icon (bottom right) to switch to numeric input, the blue markers will change to input fields and you can enter the values.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The **Page Margins **are the general limits of the entire page content including the left and upper static page region. (By default, the right region is outside the right page margin, the lower region is in the bottom page margin and displaces the body region as far as necessary).

The **Body Margins **determine the available space for the body region. The body is the region for all "normal" contents, i.e. for all except the contents of the static regions.

The **Extents **must be set additionally if the static page regions are filled and require space. Otherwise the static contents would extend into the body region. Conversely, the extents can be used to create intentionally overlapping content like background graphics or watermarks.

With *Maximize all Extents *the expansions are set to the same values as the body margins. This ensures that the static page regions do not overlap the body region. Use the eraser icon to remove the entered values, so again only the page margins are relevant.

To become familiar with the principle of page margins, body margins and extents, it is recommended to test and observe the effects of them with different values in a sample document.

If you need mirrored page settings for double-sided documents, use the "Double Sided" option. This will automatically create two subordinate Page Masters for which you can apply different settings, under "&lt;name&gt;#1" the settings for all the odd numbered pages, under &lt;name&gt;#2 the settings for all the even pages.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The "Double Sided" option causes the static page region to be doubled, i.e. two headers, two footers etc. However, by default, they are always set to the same value, i.e. the contents you enter e.g. in the footer for the even pages are automatically the contents of the odd pages as well.

## Quick page layout change - create and apply page master
As mentioned above, the page settings are called page master. By default, there is one Page Master called "A4".

There can be any number of page masters. For example, if you want a different page layout only for testing purposes, without changing the original one, you can create and assign a new page master.

### Create page master:
- Switch to the page master view and make sure that the category "Compound" is selected. Then use the plus symbol in the upper right corner to create a new page master.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,) Alternatively, you can also copy the existing page master by clicking the: ![](data:image/png;base64,) icon when you mouse over the name.

- Change the name of the new page master if needed.

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

- Click on the new page master and apply the desired settings on the right.

**Apply page master**: assign the new page layout in the template to the page sequence:

- Switch to the editor and select the element "A4 (page sequence)" in the outline.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,) 

- You can select the new page layout from the list under *Style &amp; Properties *&gt; *Page Master*.

### Notes on page master names and selection:
*Attention! If you change the name of a page master that is already in use, you must reassign the page master to the page sequence! Otherwise the document cannot be rendered anymore.*

*The Settings icon next to the pager master selection enables you to quickly switch to the page master view.*

*Use the eraser icon to remove the currently assigned page master - keep in mind that the document can no longer be rendered.*

*The selection list shows the three categories of page masters: Compound - all "standard" page masters appear in this category, because they could theoretically be double-sided and thus composed of two subordinate page masters. Simple - all non-duplex page masters and the simple page masters of duplex page masters. Complex - see the following chapter.*

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

## Different page layouts in one document - complex page masters
If you need different page settings within a document and if you need different static page regions, you have to create a "Complex Page Master". This may be because the first page should have different page margins, or even a different header than the rest of the pages. Or because pages in landscape format are required within the document.

Complex page masters are composed of simple page masters. Proceed as follows:

- First create the required simple page masters in the *Compound *category, e.g. an additional page master for the first page or for landscape pages. The best way to do this, is to create copies of the existing page masters and modify them - this way you can make sure that all settings are consistent except for the modified ones.

- Switch to the *Complex *category and create a new page master by clicking the plus symbol.

- Click on the page master and select the required simple page masters on the right (checkboxes).

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,) 

> Note

*You must set this step in any case. If there is a complex page master without an assigned simple page master, the document cannot be rendered.*

- Define the sequence in which the page masters will be applied to the document pages.

Arrow buttons appear when you mouse over the page master on the right. Specify how many pages the page master should be applied to (for each pagemaster), and check the option "Repeated Layout" for the standard pages (the number of pages entered are not relevant in this case).

Example 1: a page master for the title page is applied on the first page, page master "A4" is set for the remaining pages.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Example 2: The title page is followed by two pages in landscape format, all remaining pages are set in portrait format.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Example 3: The title page is followed by as many portrait pages as necessary, the last page is always in landscape format (More than one differently laid out page cannot follow after the "standard" ones with repeated layout).

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Assign the complex page master to the page sequence element of the template.

> Note

*To ensure that the correct contents are placed on the correct pages, use the options for controlling the page break - see Chapter. *[Page Break](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-business-designer-user-guide-structure-of-templates-working-with-content#text-elements-text-editing).

### Different static page content:
If you use a complex page master, the static page regions are available multiple times. This allows you to define different headers or footers for the first page and for all the other pages.

However, you must first change the region names in the page settings. By default, the page regions are set to the same name. It only is possible to fill the respective headers or footers differently if the region names are different.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Attention! Use this option with caution. If you apply a complex page master where area names have been changed, you must keep it. Applying a different page master will result in the document never being able to be rendered again.*

## Use page masters across all files - page master collection
You can create page masters that you use frequently in a page master collection. This allows the page master to be used in any number of templates.

Create a collection file of the type "Page-master Package".

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

In this file you can create any number of page masters as described above the rest of the file remains empty.

To use this page master in a new template, you have to include the collection: use the ![](data:image/png;base64,)  -icon ("Add External Page Master") in the page master view, select the collection file and import it.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The available page masters in the collection are then displayed in the selection list below the local page masters.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

If you mouse over the name of the included collection, you can see where it is stored; with the ![](data:image/png;base64,) -icon you can disconnect from the collection, with the ![](data:image/png;base64,) -icon you can open the collection.

> Note

*Make sure that there are no local and external page masters with the same name. You will get an error when multiple page masters have the same name.*

To use a page master from the collection, assign it to the Page Sequence element just like local page masters. The ![](data:image/png;base64,)-icon in the selection list indicates the external page master.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

> Note

*There is a name conflict if the page master name is displayed in red.*

*The location of the linked page master collection is stored internally with a relative path. If the files are moved, the program won’t be able to find them. In this case remove the linked collection and import it again.*
